In <strnlghtCA9xJE.7It@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>In article <a_rubin.742754815@dn66> a_rubin@dsg4.dse.beckman.com (Arthur Rubin) writes:

>>
>>Not exactly.  As patent law is (at least primarily) civil law, as opposed
>>to criminal law, one could make a good case that any use of a patented
>>proceedure is legal until challenged.

>I don't see how this can be so, since after a successful suit for
>infringement, damages will accrue from the time of the infringing use, not
>from the time of the suit. Thus the court would have confirmed that the use
>of the patented procedure was "illegal" (legal scholars would say
>"infringing") before the challenge.

We're just arguing over definitions.  However, "infringing" does not imply
"illegal", and nothing is infringing unless the infringement suit is
brought.
